  "paper_analysis": {
    "method_summary": "HippoRAG is a neurobiologically inspired retrieval framework for LLMs modeled after the hippocampal memory indexing theory. In an offline indexing stage, an instruction-tuned LLM extracts a schemaless open knowledge graph from each passage using a two-step process: named entity extraction followed by OpenIE triple extraction. The resulting noun-phrase nodes and relation edges form an artificial hippocampal index, while a retrieval encoder adds synonymy edges between semantically similar nodes when cosine similarity exceeds a threshold. This also defines a node-to-passage incidence matrix counting noun phrase occurrences in passages. During online retrieval, the same LLM extracts named entities from the query, a retrieval encoder links each query entity to the most similar KG node, and these matched query nodes seed a Personalized PageRank computation over the KG. The resulting node probabilities are aggregated back to passages to rank them for retrieval, enabling single-step multi-hop retrieval across passage boundaries. The method uses node specificity weighting and can also be plugged into iterative retrieval pipelines such as IRCoT.",
    "key_formulas": [
      "R_{q}=\\{r_{1},...,r_{n}\\}\\text{ such that }r_{i}=e_{k}\\text{ where }k=\\operatorname*{arg\\,max}_{j}\\,\\mathrm{cosine\\_similarity}(M(c_i), M(e_j))",
      "\\tau",
      "\\text{PPR damping factor}=0.5"
    ],
